The Live Well Social Enterprises programme is working to increase access to affordable healthcare, supports livelihoods and stimulates economic development in communities in Zambia.

The main goal of CARE's response is to sucessfuly contribute to the EBOLA EPR Plan Gola: To reduce the incidence and mortality due to Ebola Virus.Our specific Objective is to increase Community awareness on Ebola prevention

CARE plans to provide relief to the affected people in Supaul district through distribution of non-food items (NFI). As per CARE assessment in Supaul district, Marauna and Nirmali blocks are among the most affected. Supaul, Kisanpur, Saraigarh-Bhaptiyahi and Basantpur being the other four most affected in Supaul.CARE will carry out relief distribution viz. Shelter NFI*; WASH NFI. Based on the needs prioritised by affected community during the assessments, CARE will be providing assistance in WASH and Shelter.

CARE proposes to improve the lives of 12,500 pastoralists (51% women) and 600 students in 4 schools, (30% girls) in Dalifage woreda (district), through increased, improved and more sustainable sanitation and hygiene as well as water for productive and domestic use. Programming will promote women and girls' empowerment; link the initiative to wider gender transformation and strengthen government and community capacities and coordinated engagement.

CARE aims to to meet the life-saving WASH and temporary shelter needs of the most vulnerable population, especially women and girls, affected by monsoon flooding in NRS by improving water and sanitation access and temporary shelter for 5,080 HH without access to clean water in Buthiduang and housing damages.

CARE UK response strategy focuses on life-saving assistance through WASH, Shelter/NFI, SRH, FNS and protection/GBV, primarily in new spontaneous sites. In particular, CARE will aim to create a protective environment for women and girls and will provide services and facilities that respond to their specific assistance and protection needs. Secondly, CARE aims to create an enabling environment that supports women and girls empowerment and leadership in humanitarian decision-making.

CARE intends to use ?150,000 of Jersey Overseas Aid funding to maintain its Rapid Response Mechanism, enabling flexible and life-saving humanitarian assistance to meet complex and critical basic needs of displaced families in Yemen.

CARE Uganda (CUG) is currently providing assistance to South Sudanese refugees in terms of interventions on maternal health, WASH, GBV, livelihoods; and shelter to influxes of South Sudanese refugees in Uganda due to the conflict and food crisis in neighbouring South Sudan.
